03:52.167 --> 03:56.967
Uh, first of all, we've got this set
of regulation handcuffs

03:57.100 --> 03:59.767
like you might find laying around
your bedroom at home, you know?

03:59.833 --> 04:01.233
(AUDIENCE LAUGHS)

04:01.367 --> 04:04.433
Also inside here,
I have another suitcase.

04:04.967 --> 04:07.900
Inside this suitcase
I keep something very special.

04:07.967 --> 04:08.967
(RATTLING)

04:09.033 --> 04:11.033
This is my ball-peen hammer.

04:11.367 --> 04:12.800
It's used for, uh...

04:12.900 --> 04:14.700
-Peening balls.
-Yeah.

04:15.400 --> 04:17.333
And if you've ever had your ball
peened before,

04:17.466 --> 04:18.800
you know it's very unpleasant.

04:18.899 --> 04:19.966
-Okay.
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHS)

04:20.067 --> 04:21.666
Also, another suitcase.

04:22.132 --> 04:25.633
And inside this one, I keep
something else very special.

04:25.733 --> 04:27.633
This bowling ball.

04:28.800 --> 04:29.800
(CLEARS THROAT)

04:30.667 --> 04:31.667
That's good.

04:35.133 --> 04:36.500
But this is not just any bowling ball.

04:36.567 --> 04:39.033
This is the Black Onyx Strike Master 3000.

04:39.100 --> 04:40.700
Penn and Teller,
I'd like you to have a look.

04:40.767 --> 04:42.467
Uh, it's hammer time.
There you go.

04:42.533 --> 04:44.333
-Ooh, can't touch this.
-(ALL LAUGH)

04:46.733 --> 04:48.533
I know, '90s reference.
And, Teller, would you please

04:48.600 --> 04:50.367
examine the ball?
What I'd like you to do, Penn,

04:50.433 --> 04:51.733
hit the ball, notice its tonality,

04:51.800 --> 04:52.900
make sure it's solid.

04:52.967 --> 04:54.400
Uh, check it for any soft spots.

04:54.467 --> 04:55.467
(THUDS)

04:57.667 --> 04:58.800
No hinges...

04:58.867 --> 04:59.867
(ALL LAUGH)

04:59.933 --> 05:01.100
Watch Teller's thumbs.

05:01.167 --> 05:02.433
He needs them
for the sleight of hand.

05:02.500 --> 05:03.700
Okay, cool?

05:03.767 --> 05:04.900
(ALL LAUGH)

05:04.967 --> 05:06.833
-Having a little too much fun with that.
-Yes.

05:06.933 --> 05:08.833
Wow, your attention
to detail is staggering.

05:08.900 --> 05:10.000
-Thank you so much.
-(ALL LAUGH)

05:10.067 --> 05:11.967
I'll take the hammer.
You're starting to scare me.

05:12.067 --> 05:13.300
(CHUCKLES) Okay, good, here we go.

05:13.400 --> 05:14.600
All right, back up here.

05:14.667 --> 05:17.700
Now, this bowling ball weighs
exactly eight pounds.

05:17.833 --> 05:20.367
It's exactly the same size
as a human head.

05:20.700 --> 05:23.633
In fact, it's exactly the same size
as Puck's head.

05:23.767 --> 05:26.433
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHS)
-See? Look, twins.

05:26.533 --> 05:27.833
(AUDIENCE LAUGHS)

05:28.467 --> 05:29.633
What? You don't see it?

05:30.433 --> 05:31.567
How about from this side?

05:32.567 --> 05:33.733
(ALL LAUGHING)

05:36.567 --> 05:37.900
(LAUGHS)

05:39.500 --> 05:40.567
All right, we're gonna
try one more thing.

05:40.633 --> 05:42.267
Jonathan, would you help us
for a second? Thanks.

05:42.333 --> 05:44.400
-(AUDIENCE APPLAUDS)
-If you would, step behind the jail there.

05:44.467 --> 05:45.967
-Sure. Okay.
-And check the bars first.

05:46.033 --> 05:47.033
-Make sure they don't move again.
-Yeah.

05:47.100 --> 05:49.067
-This is a familiar view.
-(ALL LAUGH)

05:50.100 --> 05:52.133
And if you would, try to pass
the bowling ball through there.

05:52.200 --> 05:53.267
Sure.

05:53.333 --> 05:54.500
(RATTLING)

05:56.200 --> 05:57.967
ALEXANDER: See, the bars are staggered
in such a way

05:58.033 --> 06:00.300
that no matter how you try to shove it,
it won't go through, right?

06:00.367 --> 06:01.667
No angle works,
it won't go through.

06:01.733 --> 06:03.267
Yeah, the bars
are only five inches apart.

06:03.333 --> 06:05.200
The ball is actually
nine inches in diameter.

06:05.267 --> 06:06.500
Completely impossible.

06:06.567 --> 06:08.633
(CHUCKLES) But now we're going
to actually try to attempt

06:08.700 --> 06:10.833
to pass solid through solid.

06:10.900 --> 06:12.300
(MUSIC PLAYING ON SPEAKERS)

06:21.133 --> 06:22.567
(AUDIENCE CHEERING AND APPLAUDING)

06:28.533 --> 06:30.300
Thank you very much.
I'd like you to check this out.

06:30.367 --> 06:32.067
Why don't you get... Ooh!

06:32.167 --> 06:33.933
(ALL LAUGH)

06:39.567 --> 06:41.433
That one last bit
of security, folks.

06:41.567 --> 06:44.567
Uh, this set of handcuffs,
uh, that was on loan

06:44.633 --> 06:46.833
from the Las Vegas
Police Department.

06:46.900 --> 06:49.267
I'm gonna lock Puck
inside just like this.

06:49.633 --> 06:52.833
Now, you'll notice his hands
are locked through the bars.

06:52.900 --> 06:53.967
That's important.

06:54.200 --> 06:57.000
Now, we've seen an inanimate
object pass through.

06:57.133 --> 06:59.900
Now it's time to see
what happens when warm flesh

07:00.267 --> 07:01.733
meets cold steel.

07:01.900 --> 07:03.500
(ROCK MUSIC PLAYING ON SPEAKER)

07:18.667 --> 07:20.400
(AUDIENCE CHEERING AND APPLAUDING)

07:31.667 --> 07:33.600
ROSS: Scott and Puck,
ladies and gentlemen.

07:33.667 --> 07:34.867
Let's hear it for them.

07:35.633 --> 07:37.400
Great job. Great fun.

07:37.467 --> 07:38.467
-(APPLAUSE CONTINUES)
-Thank you.

07:38.533 --> 07:40.667
You had them with the bowling
ball going over there then.

07:40.733 --> 07:42.367
So, Penn and Teller are gonna
have a think about it.

07:42.433 --> 07:44.200
They're gonna talk about whether
they know how you did that.

07:44.267 --> 07:46.067
It was a great act, I thought.
I enjoyed it thoroughly.

07:46.133 --> 07:47.567
Uh, let me ask you
a few questions about yourself.

07:47.667 --> 07:48.833
-You're both dads, I know that.
-PUCK: Yes.

07:48.900 --> 07:50.833
You both have children.
So, your kids must love

07:50.900 --> 07:52.033
having dads who do tricks.

07:52.100 --> 07:54.267
Yes, yeah, it's kind of fun
'cause they get to show off

07:54.333 --> 07:56.933
to all their friends, you know,
that their father does magic tricks, so...

07:57.000 --> 07:58.400
His daughter is quite the magician.

07:58.467 --> 08:00.100
-Oh, really?
-Yeah, she's really good.

08:00.167 --> 08:01.833
-She does the cups and balls trick...
-How old is she now?

08:01.900 --> 08:03.700
I got one that's three
and one that's nine.

08:03.767 --> 08:05.333
-Wow, so this would be the three-year-old?
-Yes.

08:05.400 --> 08:06.700
(ALL LAUGH)

08:06.767 --> 08:08.967
Uh, but the moment
I think that I most enjoyed

08:09.033 --> 08:11.833
and I know everyone did here...
Because I could see

08:11.900 --> 08:13.333
that you were gonna
do something funny on stage

08:13.400 --> 08:14.733
when you tripped
with the bowling ball,

08:14.800 --> 08:15.933
it wasn't just Penn and Teller.

08:16.000 --> 08:17.700
It was, like, everyone
over on that side of the audience.

08:17.767 --> 08:18.933
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHS)
-I think that should qualify

08:19.000 --> 08:20.033
as fooling them right there.

08:20.100 --> 08:22.467
I think you fooled them
in that moment so, you know,

08:22.533 --> 08:24.800
if that's all it takes,
then you've done it.

08:24.867 --> 08:26.333
Okay, I think you're ready.
Are you, guys?

08:26.433 --> 08:28.333
I'm gonna start by saying

08:28.767 --> 08:32.299
the switching the bowling ball
for a balloon

08:33.067 --> 08:34.900
is a gag that I know.

08:35.433 --> 08:40.267
I've seen other magicians do it
and I always laugh with glee

08:40.433 --> 08:41.799
when people fall for it.

08:41.866 --> 08:43.267
(ALL LAUGH)

08:43.767 --> 08:46.500
I don't know what it was.

08:47.667 --> 08:49.300
Maybe it's your acting,

08:49.867 --> 08:51.900
maybe it's the timing in the bit,

08:52.667 --> 08:53.933
but you...

08:54.300 --> 08:56.433
Got me 100%...

08:56.533 --> 08:59.033
-(LAUGHING)
-...with the bowling ball.

08:59.100 --> 09:00.733
(AUDIENCE APPLAUDING)

09:03.400 --> 09:07.733
I tell you, the bowling ball
thing scared the living Jesus out of me.

09:07.800 --> 09:08.800
(AUDIENCE LAUGHS)

09:08.933 --> 09:10.467
-That's hard to do.
-And I'm an atheist.

09:10.833 --> 09:12.367
(LAUGHING)

09:13.733 --> 09:18.300
This trick, uh, is a wonderful trick.
You added to it.

09:18.567 --> 09:20.900
You added to it.
I think the handcuffs is yours, right?

09:21.333 --> 09:23.533
PENN: And the handcuffs
is a really nice addition.

09:23.600 --> 09:26.333
It makes the topological puzzle
element of it

09:26.400 --> 09:27.433
much more complicated.

09:27.500 --> 09:29.600
That's a huge wrinkle

09:29.667 --> 09:31.033
to add to this trick.

09:31.200 --> 09:34.900
Having said that, pictures sometimes speak
louder than words.

09:34.967 --> 09:38.933
Teller's got a little picture
of the trick to show you.

09:39.033 --> 09:40.800
He's quite a little sketch artist there.

09:40.867 --> 09:43.000
Don't throw any bowling balls
at him yet!

09:43.067 --> 09:44.367
(ALL LAUGHING)

09:44.567 --> 09:45.567
(CHUCKLES)

09:46.600 --> 09:47.867
-Yeah, yeah.
-Yeah.

09:48.733 --> 09:50.967
Yeah, I would say,
uh, that's how it works.

09:51.033 --> 09:52.233
Yeah, he's got it.

09:52.300 --> 09:54.233
As always we're gonna
destroy the evidence...

09:54.300 --> 09:55.533
-Yes.
-(ALL LAUGH)

09:55.900 --> 09:57.600
...so that it doesn't fall
into the wrong hands.

09:57.667 --> 09:59.200
(WHIRRING)

10:00.033 --> 10:01.833
Let's hear it for our magic
shredder, ladies and gentlemen.

10:01.933 --> 10:03.367
(AUDIENCE APPLAUDING)

10:04.900 --> 10:06.500
ROSS: Let's hear it
for Scott and Puck.

10:06.567 --> 10:07.900
Thank you, gentlemen. Great job.

10:07.967 --> 10:09.000
Thank you, Puck.

10:10.100 --> 10:11.333
Fabulous, wasn't it?

10:12.200 --> 10:14.800
Let's find out a little bit
about our next magician.

10:18.400 --> 10:21.267
ERIC JONES: <i>My name is Eric Jones</i>
<i>and I live in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.</i>

10:21.967 --> 10:23.200
<i>Now, when I first got into magic,</i>

10:23.267 --> 10:24.500
<i>I kind of used it</i>
<i>as a social crutch.</i>

